The paper proposes a new approach for spatio-temporal action localization in videos using a detector that operates on sequences of frames. This involves extracting convolutional features for each frame and using temporal stacking to generate scores and regressions. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the use of machine learning techniques such as the SSD framework suggests that the paper could also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG, cs.AI) sub-categories. The focus on video analysis and the use of bounding boxes and cuboids suggests that the paper could also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category. Finally, the use of temporal continuity and the generation of tubelets suggests that the paper could also belong to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category.
